properties.name: Cognoscenti Coffee
properties.description: Cognescenti on Washington Blvd is the best cup of coffee I have ever had in America. The pastries from Proof bakery that they carry can make any morning into an amazing day.

properties.name: Muddy Leek
properties.description: I like the Muddy Leek for cocktails, and the frequently-changing (and generously economical) wine list make it a good spot for a happy hour meeting. The daily pizzetta and the merguez hot dog are my favorite snacks.

properties.name: EK Valley Restaurant
properties.description: Excellent Oaxacan cuisine. The chicken taquitos have saved me during those days where you forget to eat because you are working at such a pace.

properties.name: JR's BBQ
properties.description: There is no tricky install challenge that cannot be resolved by contemplating a rack of ribs.

properties.name: Blum & Poe
properties.description: The first gallery to open in Culver, Blum and Poe spearheaded the move to the area in 2003. Now they are one of the most established galleries in Los Angeles, and the US, representing a wide selection of local and international artists including Takashi Murakami.

properties.name: Mandrake
properties.description: The Mandrake Bar is at the center of the Culver City Arts District. Opening in the early days of the gallery influx, this watering hole has been a consistent fixture for post-opening parties and gallery events for almost ten years. The bar has a pleasant back patio and large mural by Blum & Poe artist Dave Muller.

properties.name: Carter & Citizen
properties.description: Carter and Citizen have been the most important compliment to my programming this year! Whitney and I have so many shared interests, but our programs provide distinctly different experiences. I think our two spaces make for a can't-lose proposition for anyone willing to stoll down Little La Cienega

properties.name: Susanne Vielmetter Los Angeles Projects
properties.description: The third gallery to open in Culver City, Susanne Vielmetter is located off the main drag of La Cienega Boulevard on Washington.

properties.name: International Art Objects
properties.description: Once a mainstay of the Chinatown galleries, International Art Objects (formerly China Art Objects) relocated to Culver City in September of 2010.
